Vectores

R no trabaja solamente con variables, sino que mayormente lo hace con vectores. La lÃ³gica para la creaciÃ³n de los mismos es similar, solo que vectores pueden ser mÃ¡s amplios.

Si un vector incluye diferentes tipos de datos, toma por default para todo el grupo las carÃ¡cteristicas del Ãºltimo ingresado.

Otras maneras de crear vectores:

v <- 1:7 # same as c(1,2,3,4,5,6,7)
v <- rep(0, 77) # repeat zero 77 times: v is a vector of 77 zeroes
v <- rep(1:3, times=2) # Repeat 1,2,3 twice
v <- rep(1:10, each=2) # Repeat each element twice
v <- seq(10,20,2) # sequence: numbers between 10 and 20, in jumps of 2
v1 <- 1:5 # 1,2,3,4,5
v2 <- rep(1,5) # 1,1,1,1,1

Es posible realizar operaciones entre vectores siempre que sean del mismo tamaÃ±o

v1 + v2 # Element-wise addition
v1 + 1 # Add 1 to each element
v1 * 2 # Multiply each element by 2
v1 + c(1,7) # This doesn't work: (1,7) is a vector of different length

TambiÃ©n se pueden realizar operaciones al interior del propio vectore

sum(v1) # The sum of all elements
mean(v1) # The average of all elements
sd(v1) # The standard deviation
cor(v1,v1*5) # Correlation between v1 and v1*5

Y tambiÃ©n realizar operaciones lÃ³gicas que devuelvan un TRUE / FALSE de resultado

v1 > 2 # Each element is compared to 2, returns logical vector
v1==v2 # Are corresponding elements equivalent, returns logical vector.

The description of an igraph object starts with up to four letters: 1. D or U, for a directed or undirected graph 2. N for a named graph (where nodes have a name attribute) 3. W for a weighted graph (where edges have a weight attribute) 4. B for a bipartite (two-mode) graph (where nodes have a type attribute) The two numbers that follow (7 5) refer to the number of nodes and edges in the graph. The description also lists node & edge attributes, for example: . (g/c) - graph-level character attribute . (v/c) - vertex-level character attribute . (e/n) - edge-level numeric attribute
